myths.Agent_1:
{
  "myth": "In the Era of Dust, King Thalath stood before the parched tribes and swore the Covenant of the Deep. To end the Great Drought, he vowed that no ruler of his line would ever drink more than a single cup of water each day. To bind this oath, he severed his own shadow and staked it to the Well of Ages, tethering his spirit to the dry earth.

Centuries later, Prince Elian discovered the Hidden Grotto. Before him lay the Pool of Stars, whose waters granted eternal life and absolute power. The temptation was agonizing; his throat burned, and the water whispered promises of godhood. He knelt and plunged his face toward the surface, but as the water neared his lips, his body became agonizingly heavy, as if the earth itself were pulling him into the stone.

The consequence was literal: the oath had turned the lineage into the land’s anchors. To break the vow was to be reclaimed by the soil. Elian pulled away, his breath returning as the crushing weight lifted. Now, every heir knows that their restraint is the only thing keeping them from becoming part of the silent crust. The covenant is no longer a promise; it is the physical law of their existence."
}

